:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/6E21A7D6-BE0F-45B5-9AAD-25FE1CE982B1"><gtr:id>6E21A7D6-BE0F-45B5-9AAD-25FE1CE982B1</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Charles</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>ffrench-Constant</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/070AF2F0-F5AE-4A96-B29B-FE72A23E1FF5"><gtr:id>070AF2F0-F5AE-4A96-B29B-FE72A23E1FF5</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Joanna</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Wardlaw</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_PC_16031"><gtr:id>3DA7AAD2-F604-48B1-993D-6E4AF4813826</gtr:id><gtr:title>University of Edinburgh Momentum Award ? Dementias</gtr:title><gtr:status>Active</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_PC_16031</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Abstracts are not currently available in GtR for all funded research. This is normally because the abstract was not required at the time of proposal submission, but may be because it included sensitive information such as personal details.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Understanding and treating dementia requires an approach that looks beyond the neuron and
considers the interactions between cellular and systemic influences that originate on (and span)
both sides of the blood-brain-barrier. Edinburgh?s strategy is therefore an integrated brain and
body, life-course approach that allies molecular/cellular approaches with animal cognitive
studies, human experimental medicine, and the use of deeply phenotyped and stratified human
cohorts for discovery science.
This interdisciplinary vision sets Edinburgh apart from other UK centres and offers a distinct
route to novel targets and strategies for prevention. It will be achieved by bringing together the
international excellence in neuro-glial interactions and synapse-to-cognition of Edinburgh
Neuroscience with our MRC, BHF, MS Society and UKRPIF-funded Centres and Institutes in
Regenerative Medicine, Vascular Regeneration, Inflammation Research and Tissue Repair.
These strengths, embedded in a world-leading health data environment and forward/reverse
translation capability, provide an opportunity to initiate new synergistic activity involving experts
in different systems, cell types and technologies to drive novel approaches to discovery in
neurodegenerative disease.
To exploit this opportunity, we seek a Momentum Award to build Edinburgh and UK capacity
in dementia research in two ways. First, by pump-priming new projects that focus our young
high-flyers working in other areas of neuroscience on innovative collaborative projects examining
pathogenesis and target discovery in neurodegeneration. Second, by recruiting a new Chair in
Neuro-inflammation to build capacity, complement our strengths in neuronal, vascular and
metabolic processes, and synergise within Edinburgh experts in non-CNS inflammation. These
investments will enable the Dementia Research Institute to develop interdisciplinary research
programmes required to address the generational challenge of dementia.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2020-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2017-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>518259</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>9713CFF7-CCED-4786-92E6-14C4D7E96607</gtr:id><gtr:title>Pluripotent Stem Cells for Uncovering the Role of Mitochondria in Human Brain Function and Dysfunction.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of molecular biology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8ad79fe98d2b0d322c175897ccf90e22"><gtr:id>8ad79fe98d2b0d322c175897ccf90e22</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Zink A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2018-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0022-2836</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>5aa677a2212955.07769939</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>247F6103-85E8-4FC6-957C-FEDCE9588C3C</gtr:id><gtr:title>Patrolling monocytes sense peripheral infection and induce cytokine-mediated neuronal dysfunction.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Nature medicine</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/edaef4be879827e060fbe1b8c835e960"><gtr:id>edaef4be879827e060fbe1b8c835e960</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Priller J</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:d